. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1FC7A804911100E6" box="[233,308,368,390]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
. Coloration: body reddish to dark-brown, with the elytra sometimes slightly paler and the elytral postero-lateral angles weakly infuscate; legs yellowish to yellowishbrown; antennae reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF4BD5E1F9CA8A4922B03D2" blockId="11.[178,1086,464,690]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">
Head (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1FD6A8A491610086" box="[248,324,464,486]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) of transversely rectangular shape, approximately 1.15 times as broad as long; posterior margin distinctly concave in the middle; punctation distinct and dense; interstices narrower than diameter of punctures and glossy, without microsculpture; sides with long dark-brown setae. Eyes large, on average approximately as long as postocular portion in dorsal view, often slightly shorter or longer. Antennae slender, 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF4BD5E1CEBAB319418033A" box="[965,1085,581,603]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.1">1.1-1.2 mm</quantity>
long; preapical antennomeres approximately as wide as long. Anterior margin of labrum with broadly V-shaped excision in the middle; left mandible with three, right mandible with four pronounced molar teeth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF4BD5E1F9CABB794250250" blockId="11.[178,1085,706,816]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1E0BABB6915503B8" box="[293,368,706,728]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.2 times as wide as long and 1.05 times as broad as head; posterior angles rounded, weakly marked; lateral and anterior margins with long dark setae; punctation very dense and distinctly, finely granulose, rendering the pronotum matt; with or without rudiment of an impunctate median band in posterior half.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF4BD5E1F9CAA4B92F302CC" blockId="11.[178,1086,831,941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1E2FAA4B91680235" box="[257,333,831,853]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) 1.10-1.15 times as long as pronotum; punctation very dense, fine, and somewhat asperate. Hind wings fully developed. Protarsomeres I-IV sexually dimorphic, more distinctly dilated in males than in females. Metatarsomere I longer than II and slightly shorter than the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF4BD5E1F9CAAC893A2028F" blockId="11.[178,1085,956,1007]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Abdomen narrower than elytra; punctation extremely fine and dense, barely noticeable in the microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF4BD5E1FE9AA8B913905E9" blockId="11.[178,1085,1023,1161]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">
: sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1E71AA8B918E0575" box="[351,427,1023,1045]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
) with weakly concave posterior margin; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1CC7AA8B94100575" box="[1001,1077,1023,1045]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
) oblong and with posterior excision of trapezoid shape (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1DDAAD6893660552" box="[756,835,1052,1074]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
); aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1CEAAD6894130552" box="[964,1078,1052,1074]" captionStart="Figs 26-35" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[187,1087,216,1505]" captionTargetId="figure-2@12.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 26-35: Orsunius granulosus nov.sp. (26-32), O. latexcisus nov.sp. (33) and O. flavovirgatus nov.sp. (34-35): (26) habitus; (27) forebody; (28) male sternite VII; (29, 33, 34) male sternite VIII; (30, 35) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (31) aedeagus in lateral view; (32) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 26-27: 1.0 mm; 28-29, 31-34: 0.2 mm; 30, 35: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Figs 31-32</figureCitation>
) small, approximately 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF4BD5E1EBEAD4D91CF052F" box="[400,490,1081,1103]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" unit="mm" value="0.35">0.35 mm</quantity>
long; internal sac with a pair of strongly sclerotized short and curved apical structures and with a pair of longer, less strongly sclerotized basal structures.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8FB6574FFF4BD5E1F9CADED91FC04F9" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF4BD5E1F9CADED91FC04F9" blockId="11.[178,1085,1177,1433]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">
Comparative notes: This and the two following species are attributed to 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF4BD5E1F9CADC3912B05AC" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2011" box="[178,270,1207,1228]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF4BD5E1F9CADC3912B05AC" box="[178,270,1207,1228]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Orsunius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with some hesitation. They share the habitus, the head shape, and other external characters with the species previously assigned to the genus, but are distinguished from them by the presence of four (rather than three) molar teeth on the right mandible, the broadly V-shaped median incision of the anterior margin of the labrum, the conspicuous granulose punctation of the pronotum, and by a rather different morphology of the aedeagus. From the closely related 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF4BD5E1D1EAC3D928B043F" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[560,686,1353,1375]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneatus">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF4BD5E1D1EAC3D928B043F" box="[560,686,1353,1375]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">O. cuneatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF4BD5E1DC7AC3D9363043F" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[745,838,1353,1375]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heissi">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF4BD5E1DC7AC3D9363043F" box="[745,838,1353,1375]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">O. heissi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF4BD5E1C77AC3D93C9043F" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[857,1004,1353,1375]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulosus">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF4BD5E1C77AC3D93C9043F" box="[857,1004,1353,1375]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">O. granulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is best distinguished by the trapezoid posterior excision of the male sternite VII and by the morphology of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8FB6574FFF4BD5E1F9CACDC91B70776" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF4BD5E1F9CACDC91B70776" blockId="11.[178,1085,1448,1558]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">
Distribution and natural history: The species is known from three localities in southern 
<collectingCountry id="E8F6766FFFF4BD5E1EEBACB291DC04BB" box="[453,505,1478,1499]" name="Laos" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Laos</collectingCountry>
, North 
<collectingCountry id="E8F6766FFFF4BD5E1D6BACB2928704BC" box="[581,674,1478,1500]" name="Thailand" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, and North 
<collectingCountry id="E8F6766FFFF4BD5E1C36ACB2934A04BC" box="[792,879,1478,1500]" name="Vietnam" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF4BD5E1C52ACB293E704BC" box="[892,962,1478,1500]" captionStart="Map 2" captionStartId="2.[178,223,1075,1095]" captionTargetBox="[178,1092,212,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-2@2.[178,1092,212,1064]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Map 2: Distributions of Orsunius gladiator (white and black circles), O. latexcisus (black circle), O. flavovirgatus (black circle), O. heissi (black star), O. stimulans (black and grey triangles), O. granulosus (white and grey triangles), O. cuneatus (white diamond), and O. spathulatus (black square)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305061/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Map 2</figureCitation>
). The partly teneral specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="E8F6766FFFF4BD5E1E84AC9091FE0499" box="[426,475,1508,1529]" name="Laos" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Laos</collectingCountry>
were sifted from leaf litter in a degraded primary forest at an altitude of 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF4BD5E1E10AF7491A80776" box="[318,397,1536,1558]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" unit="m" value="1100.0">1100 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
